/ Tests for lib/stats.goal — load via arilib import "stats".
/ Note: in Goal, `f ,x` is parsed as the dyadic join `f , x`, not function
/ application. Use bracket notation `f[,x]` when passing an enlisted atom.

arilib import "stats"

/ --- stats.cile ---
tt.t{3~stats.cile[0.5;1 2 3 4 5]}  / median of odd list
tt.t{2~stats.cile[0.5;1 2 3 4]}    / median of even list
tt.t{2~stats.cile[0.25;1 2 3 4 5]} / Q1
tt.t{4~stats.cile[0.75;1 2 3 4 5]} / Q3
tt.t{5~stats.cile[1.0;1 2 3 4 5]}  / max via cile
tt.t{3~stats.cile[0.5;5 3 1 4 2]}  / sorts input before computing

/ --- stats.summary ---
/ All dict values are floats because the homogeneous value array unifies
/ around the float sd field.
r:stats.summary 1 2 3 4 5
tt.t{5.0~r["count"]}
tt.t{1.0~r["min"]}
tt.t{5.0~r["max"]}
tt.t{3.0~r["mean"]}
tt.t{3.0~r["median"]}
tt.t{2.0~r["q25"]}
tt.t{4.0~r["q75"]}
tt.t{1e-10>abs[r["sd"]-sqrt 2.0]}

/ summary sorts its input — same result for any permutation
r2:stats.summary 5 3 1 4 2
tt.t{5.0~r2["count"]}
tt.t{1.0~r2["min"]}
tt.t{5.0~r2["max"]}
tt.t{3.0~r2["mean"]}

1
